w:r.w:t: I'm writing this up as a note to myself and those in the performance team who may be interested.
GGL-29704 gatherObStats() : enable subpartition stats for ONEVIEW_DATA schema
, which is scheduled for Q1, and it's currently in PSP.

Don't we already have subpartition stats on ONEVIEW_DATA? Sort of. We do have some basic stats on the subpartitions, but due to a bug in the gatherObStats() proc, we do not gather subpartition stats on ONEVIEW_DATA subpartitions. This jira is to fix that.
However, after implementing the jira and gathering subpartiton stats, Nishant wrote to me yesterday to point out that a report that worked previously in PSP no longer did.
Actually it turned out that the report only ran long for certain dates. Dates prior to 20181217 were fine, 20181217 and after were not fine.
The main view in question is VW_OV_CALC_FACT_NEW_V03, which has not changed at all. This view joins OV_CALC_FACT_NEW to a number of control tables, such OV_LOAD_CONTROL and OV_CALC_CONTROL.
The problem here is that each join is using the column OV_LOAD_CONTROL_KEY. That is
the partition key for OV_CALC_FACT_NEW. OV_CALC_FACT_NEW is partitioned on OV_DAY, and subpartitioned on SUBPARTITION_IDENTIFIER, which is a VARCHAR.

The reason that the view performs poorly can be traced to the join between OV_LOAD_CONTROL and OV_CALC_FACT_NEW. Previously when there were no stats on the OV_LOAD_CONTROL_KEY column the estimates were always the same, ie 20M.

After gathering column stats on OV_LOAD_CONTROL_KEY, the optimizer is able to compare the column to the corresponding column in OV_LOAD_CONTROL. The problem here is that the column stats in the OV_LOAD_CONTROL do not reflect what is in that table itself, or indeed the OV_CALC_FACT_NEW table either. According to the column stats, the maximum value of OV_LOAD_CONTROL_KEY is
, and so optimizer concludes that the result of the join must be 0 rows. This is essentially an out of range problem.
The solution is therefore to gather stats again on OV_LOAD_CONTROL. But for this to work we will need to gather stats on OV_LOAD_CONTROL much more frequently.

Subhash, can we have a chat about this on Monday? The point here is that it's very important to have accurate stats on your control tables. We had a similar issue in Merival with the NEUTRAL_CONTROL. They now gather stats on that table after loading every workflow.
The other question I'm curious about is why these control tables join to the fact tables on a column which is not the partition key?
